Control of the whole area. Iraq ended the war an estimated $70 billion in debt. The war bills kept the government from delivering material benefits promised to the Iraqi people directly after the war. Saddam was reported to be incensed that Kuwait was demanding repayment for the wartime loans. The sentence for criticizing Saddam is death, and the president considered Kuwait's oil overproduction and the subsequent fall in the price of oil a personal affront to Iraq. Iraqi President Saddam Hussein seemed determined to solve his financial problems and fulfill territorial ambitions by dethroning the government of neighboring Kuwait. 